65","12 MAY 1166":"12. maj 1166","Abbey of Holyrood, Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Skotland, United Kingdom","Bedrule, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Bedrule, Roxburghshire, Skotland","Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Carrick, Ayrshire, Skotland","Terregles, Dumfries-shire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1090–12 MAY 1166":"1090–12 mei 1166","1090–1166":"1090–1166","1088–Female":"1088–Overleden","1124–1165":"1124–1165","1065–Male":"1065–Overleden","1065–Female":"1065–Overleden","1090":"1090","1124":"1124","1166":"1166","1165":"1165","1088":"1088","1065":"1065","about 1165":"circa 1165","12 MAY 1166":"12 mei 1166","Abbey of Holyrood, Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bedrule, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Bedrule, Roxburghshire, Schotland","Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Carrick, Ayrshire, Schotland","Terregles, Dumfries-shire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1090–12 MAY 1166":"1090–12 May 1166","1090–1166":"1090–1166","1088–Female":"1088–Deceased","1124–1165":"1124–1165","1065–Male":"1065–Deceased","1065–Female":"1065–Deceased","1090":"1090","1124":"1124","1166":"1166","1165":"1165","1088":"1088","1065":"1065","about 1165":"about 1165","12 MAY 1166":"12 May 1166","Abbey of Holyrood, Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom","Bedrule, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Bedrule, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland","Terregles, Dumfries-shire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacDonald","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:  see  McDonald  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McDonald","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac Domhnaill</i> ‘son of <i>Domhnall</i>’, a name derived from the Celtic elements <i>domno-</i> ‘world’ + <i>val-</i> ‘might, rule’. <i>Donald</i> is an Anglicized form (via Latin) of this personal name used in Scotland, though the surname is also widespread in Ireland. The name is equivalent to Irish   McDonnell   and   McConnell  , and to Manx   Cannell  .","History: This is the name of the largest and most disparate of the Scottish clans (Clan Donald), associated in particular with the Hebrides and claiming descent from Domhnall mac Raghnaill mac Somhairle, who lived in the late 12th century. From that time until 1493 the head of the clan was known as Lord (or King) of the Isles. The reigns of the Lords of the Isles were always stormy, often in conflict with the kings of Scotland, and peppered with disasters. After a series of defeats in the 1480s, Eoin Mac Dhomhnaill a Ìle (John Macdonald of Islay, Earl of Ross and Lord of the Isles) forfeited his lands, his power, and his title as Lord of the Isles in 1493 to King James IV of Scotland. By then, a branch of the family had settled in the Antrim Glens in Ireland and members moved between the southern Hebrides and Ireland throughout the 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Fergus","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Fearghas , one of the Gaelic names that has recently also been favoured by parents without Irish or Scottish connections."],"variants":[{"name":"Fearghas","meanings":["From Irish <i>fear</i> ‘man’ + <i>gus</i> ‘vigour’; the name of a shadowy hero in Irish mythology, also of the grandfather of St Columba."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Fergus MacDonald 3rd Lord of Galloway was born in 1090, in Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, Donald of Galloway, was 26 and his mother, Mrs. Donald of Galloway, was 26. He married Elizabeth Joan. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 12 May 1166, in Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 76."},"et":{"1090–12 MAY 1166":"1090–12. mai 1166","1090–1166":"1090–1166","1088–Female":"1088–Surnud","1124